      <description>&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;The Progression server most likely grew out of the common desire by many people for&amp;nbsp;a "Classic" eq server.&amp;nbsp; They can't go back to Classic, at least not easily or inexpensively, but they could do this.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;Some of the people who are/will play on Combine are returning accounts or people who would have otherwise quit the game.&amp;nbsp; If even 100 from each server left to play on Combine, that wouldn't impact any server that greatly and its 100 accounts that is still paying cash for the game.&amp;nbsp; If we get 100 people to restart their accounts, that is 100 more subscriptions than SOE has now.&amp;nbsp; There are also people out there who would like to try EQ but don't want to come into a mature server in a mature game.&amp;nbsp; This allows them a chance to keep up with the Joneses.&amp;nbsp; Again, any new subscriptions are more subscriptions.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;Some people who will be playing on combine DON'T want the expansions unlocked quickly.&amp;nbsp; They want a slower paced game.&amp;nbsp; While some people are going to try and be that uber guild, a lot of people are would probably sabotage them if they could.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;As far as the money goes, I believe the expansion costs are primarily to cover the cost of development, while the subscriptions pay for the operating expenses and profit.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;I guess I am just opposite in my viewpoint from yours on this server.&amp;nbsp; I see it as SOE trying to do something many people have been requesting for years.&amp;nbsp; I also think that if it doesn't pay for itself, it will be shut down.&amp;nbsp; So what's to lose?&amp;nbsp; While I am not in favor of taking development away from the main game, I think this server is a pretty reasonable offering.&lt;/P&gt;</description>
